'''''Psyche''''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|aɪ|k|i}} {{respell|SY|kee}}) is a NASA [[Discovery Program]] space mission launched on October 13, 2023, to explore the origin of [[planetary core]]s by orbiting and studying the metallic asteroid [[16 Psyche]] beginning in 2029.<ref name="NYT-20170106">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/06/science/nasa-psyche-asteroid.html|title=A Metal Ball the Size of Massachusetts That NASA Wants to Explore|newspaper=The New York Times|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|date=January 6, 2017|access-date=March 3, 2017|archive-date=January 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107052013/http://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/06/science/nasa-psyche-asteroid.html|url-status=live}}</ref> NASA's [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] (JPL) manages the project.

The spacecraft will orbit the asteroid from August 5, 2029, to October 31, 2031, spending 817 days in orbit. Psyche uses solar-powered [[Hall-effect thruster]]s for propulsion and orbital maneuvering, the first interplanetary spacecraft to use that technology. It is also the first mission to use [[Deep Space Optical Communications|laser optical communications]] beyond the Earth-Moon system.

== History ==
{{Main|Selection of Discovery Mission 13 and 14}}

The proposal for the ''Psyche'' mission was submitted by [[Lindy Elkins-Tanton]], a principal investigator at [[Arizona State University]], as part of a call for proposals for NASA's [[Discovery Program]] missions 13 and 14 that closed in February 2015. It was shortlisted on September 30, 2015, as one of five finalists, and awarded US$3 million for further concept development.<ref name="NYT-20170106"/><ref name="selection 1st round">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-selects-investigations-for-future-key-planetary-mission|title=NASA Selects Investigations for Future Key Planetary Mission|publisher=NASA|first1=Dwayne C.|last1=Brown|first2=Laurie|last2=Cantillo|date=September 30, 2015|access-date=October 1, 2015|archive-date=August 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809110251/https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-selects-investigations-for-future-key-planetary-mission/|url-status=live}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>

On January 4, 2017, ''Psyche'' was selected for the 14th Discovery mission, with launch set for 2023.<ref name="Brown">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-selects-two-missions-to-explore-the-early-solar-system|title=NASA Selects Two Missions to Explore the Early Solar System|publisher=NASA|first1=Dwayne C.|last1=Brown|first2=Laurie|last2=Cantillo|date=January 4, 2017|access-date=January 4, 2017|archive-date=June 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617074931/https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-selects-two-missions-to-explore-the-early-solar-system/|url-status=live}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> In May 2017, the launch date was moved up to target a more efficient trajectory, to July 2022 aboard a [[SpaceX]] [[Falcon Heavy]] launch vehicle with a January 31, 2026 arrival, following a [[Mars]] [[gravity assist]] on May 23, 2023.<ref name=sdc20200522>{{cite news|last=Mathewson|first=Samantha|title=NASA picks SpaceX Falcon Heavy to launch Psyche mission to metal asteroid in 2022|url=https://www.space.com/spacex-falcon-heavy-launching-nasa-psyche-asteroid-mission.html|date=March 2, 2020|publisher=SPACE.com|access-date=May 22, 2020|archive-date=August 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809110259/https://www.space.com/spacex-falcon-heavy-launching-nasa-psyche-asteroid-mission.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In June 2022 NASA found that the late delivery of the testing equipment and Guidance, Navigation, and Control (GNC) flight software for the ''Psyche'' spacecraft did not give them enough time to complete the required testing, and decided to delay the launch, with future windows available in 2023 and 2024 to rendezvous with the [[asteroid]] in 2029 and 2030, respectively.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last= |title=NASA Announces Launch Delay for Its Psyche Asteroid Mission |url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/nasa-announces-launch-delay-for-its-psyche-asteroid-mission |access-date=June 24, 2022 |website=NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) |language=en-US |archive-date=June 24, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220624190158/https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/nasa-announces-launch-delay-for-its-psyche-asteroid-mission |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Zurbuchen |first=Thomas H. |date=2022-11-04 |title=Summary of NASA Responses to Psyche Independent Review Board |url=https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/psyche_irb_report_and_response_nov_2022.pdf |website=www.nasa.gov}}</ref>

On October 28, 2022, NASA announced that ''Psyche'' was targeting a launch period opening on October 10, 2023, which would correspond with an arrival at the asteroid in August 2029.<ref name="jpl-20221028" />

An independent review of the delays at JPL reported in November 2022 found understaffing, insufficient planning, and communications issues among engineers and with management. The ''[[VERITAS (spacecraft)|VERITAS]]'' Venus mission was delayed to free up staff to focus on ''Psyche''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Foust |first=Jeff |date=November 5, 2022 |title=Psyche review finds institutional problems at JPL |publisher=Space News |url=https://spacenews.com/psyche-review-finds-institutional-problems-at-jpl/ |url-status=live |access-date=March 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231016053736/https://spacenews.com/psyche-review-finds-institutional-problems-at-jpl/ |archive-date=October 16, 2023}}</ref>

On April 18, 2023, JPL's mission page for ''Psyche'' was updated to reflect a new launch date of October 5, 2023.<ref name="jpl-20230427">{{cite web |title=Psyche |url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/missions/psyche |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230503003524/https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/missions/psyche |archive-date=May 3, 2023 |access-date=27 April 2023 |website=NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) - Robotic Space Exploration |publisher=NASA/JPL-Caltech}}</ref> On September 28, 2023, the launch was again delayed to no earlier than October 12, 2023, due to an unspecified issue with the spacecraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2023/09/28/launch-of-nasas-psyche-asteroid-mission-slips-a-week-due-to-spacecraft-issue/|title=Launch of NASA's Psyche asteroid mission slips a week due to spacecraft issue|date=September 28, 2023|access-date=September 28, 2023|website=spaceflightnow.com|archive-date=September 29, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929122714/https://spaceflightnow.com/2023/09/28/launch-of-nasas-psyche-asteroid-mission-slips-a-week-due-to-spacecraft-issue/|url-status=live}}</ref> After one additional delay due to bad weather, ''Psyche'' was launched successfully on October 13, 2023.<ref name="space.com_12oct2023">{{Cite web |date=2023-10-12 |title=Bad weather delays SpaceX Falcon Heavy launch of NASA's Psyche asteroid mission to Oct. 13 |url=https://www.space.com/nasa-psyche-spacex-falcon-heavy-launch-delay-weather |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231012011137/https://www.space.com/nasa-psyche-spacex-falcon-heavy-launch-delay-weather |archive-date=October 12, 2023 |access-date=2023-10-12 |website=Space.com |language=en}}</ref>

An update in May 2024 reported the spacecraft was in good health and on track to complete its mission on the planned timeline along with commencing fire of its [[Xenon|xenon thrusters]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=NASA |title=NASA's Psyche fires up its sci-fi-worthy thrusters |url=https://phys.org/news/2024-05-nasa-psyche-sci-fi-worthy.html |access-date=2024-05-23 |website=phys.org |language=en}}</ref>

In April 2025, ''Psyche'' experienced an unexpected drop in the pressure of its xenon propulsion system. The spacecraft paused its thrusting while the problem was under investigation and its system engineers considered resorting to the spacecraft's backup redundancy fuel line in order to continue the probe's thrust operation.<ref>{{cite web | title=NASA’s Psyche Mission Looking Into Propulsion System | year=2025 | publisher=NASA | url=https://science.nasa.gov/blogs/psyche/2025/04/29/nasas-psyche-mission-looking-into-propulsion-system/| access-date=2025-05-09 }}</ref> Following a switch to the backup fuel line in May, full thruster operation resumed on June 16, 2025.<ref>{{cite web | title=NASA’s Psyche Spacecraft Resumes Full-Time Propulsion | year=2025 | publisher=NASA | url=https://science.nasa.gov/blogs/psyche/2025/06/20/nasas-psyche-spacecraft-resumes-full-time-propulsion/| access-date=2025-06-20 }}</ref>

[[File:Crescent Mars Psyche.png|left|thumb|A color image of a crescent-shaped [[Mars]], taken by the Psyche space probe as it approached in May 2026.]]
On May 15, 2026, ''Psyche'' successfully flew by Mars as part of a [[gravity-assist]] maneuver that adjusted its orbital tilt around the Sun, allowing the probe and its path to align with the orbital plane of asteroid Psyche. The probe flew as close as {{convert|4500|km|abbr=on}} above the surface of the Red Planet.<ref name=mars1>{{cite web |url=https://science.nasa.gov/blogs/psyche/2026/05/08/nasas-psyche-mission-to-fly-by-mars-for-gravity-assist/ |title=NASA’s Psyche Mission to Fly by Mars for Gravity Assist | year=2026 | publisher=NASA| access-date=16 May 2026}}</ref> The probe used its multispectral imager instrument to image the planet. Because Psyche approached Mars at a high phase angle, the planet appeared as a thin crescent before the close flyby, illuminated by sunlight reflected from its surface. Images taken by the spacecraft’s multispectral cameras showed the crescent appearing brighter and stretching farther around Mars than expected because sunlight was strongly scattered by the planet’s dusty atmosphere.<ref name=mars2>{{cite web |url=https://science.nasa.gov/photojournal/nasas-psyche-mission-images-the-crescent-of-mars/ |title=NASA’s Psyche Mission Images the Crescent of Mars | year=2026 | publisher=NASA| access-date=20 May 2026}}</ref>

== Target ==
{{Main|16 Psyche}}
16 Psyche is the heaviest known [[M-type asteroid]] with a mean diameter of {{convert|220|km}}, and may be an exposed [[Planetary core|iron core]] of a [[protoplanet]],<ref name='mission'>{{cite conference|url=http://www.hou.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2014/pdf/1253.pdf|title=Journey to a Metal World: Concept for a Discovery Mission to Psyche|conference=45th Lunar and Planetary Science Conference March 17–24, 2014 The Woodlands, Texas|display-authors=1|last1=Elkins-Tanton|first1=L. T.|last2=Asphaug|first2=E.|last3=Bell|first3=J.|last4=Bercovici|first4=D.|last5=Bills|first5=B. G.|last6=Binzel|first6=Richard P.|last7=Bottke|first7=William F.|last8=Jun|first8=I.|last9=Marchi|first9=S.|last10=Oh|first10=D.|last11=Polanskey|first11=C. A.|last12=Weiss|first12=B. P.|last13=Wenkert|first13=D.|last14=Zuber|first14=M. T.|at=1253|date=2014|id=LPI Contribution No. 1777|bibcode=2014LPI....45.1253E|access-date=October 1, 2015|archive-date=February 27, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227025757/http://www.hou.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2014/pdf/1253.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> the remnant of a violent collision with another object that stripped off its [[mantle (geology)|mantle]] and [[Crust (geology)|crust]].

Recent studies show that it is "a mixed metal and silicate world".<ref name="Elkins-Tanton_2020">{{cite journal 
