== Mission overview ==
The ''Psyche'' spacecraft is designed with [[solar electric propulsion]],<ref name='SEP 2017'>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=6958|title=NASA Glenn Tests Thruster Bound for Metal World|publisher=NASA|first1=D. C.|last1=Agle|first2=Jimi|last2=Russell|first3=Laurie|last3=Cantillo|first4=Dwayne|last4=Brown|date=September 28, 2017|access-date=January 6, 2018|archive-date=April 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412010047/https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=6958|url-status=live}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name='Van 2015'>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/guest-blogs/van-kane/20140219-mission-to-a-metallic-world.html|title=Mission to a Metallic World: A Discovery Proposal to Fly to the Asteroid Psyche|publisher=The Planetary Society|first=Van|last=Kane|date=February 19, 2014|access-date=October 1, 2015|archive-date=October 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004194406/http://www.planetary.org/blogs/guest-blogs/van-kane/20140219-mission-to-a-metallic-world.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and the scientific payload includes a [[multispectral image]]r, a [[magnetometer]], and a [[gamma-ray spectrometer]].<ref name='Van 2015'/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.llnl.gov/news/lab-johns-hopkins-team-tapped-work-possible-nasa-effort-explore-asteroid-0|title=Lab-Johns Hopkins team tapped to work on possible NASA effort to explore asteroid|publisher=Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory|first=Stephen|last=Wampler|date=November 4, 2015|access-date=December 21, 2015|archive-date=August 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809110308/https://www.llnl.gov/news/lab-johns-hopkins-team-tapped-work-possible-nasa-effort-explore-asteroid-0|url-status=live}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>

The mission is designed to perform 21 months of science. The spacecraft was built by NASA [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] (JPL) in collaboration with [[SSL (company)|SSL]] (formerly Space Systems/Loral) and [[Arizona State University]].<ref name="jpl-20221028" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sslmda.com/html/pressreleases/pr20151026.html|title=SSL is JPL Industrial Partner for NASA Asteroid Exploration Mission Opportunity|publisher=SSL (company)|last=Lewis|first=Wendy|date=October 26, 2015|access-date=January 4, 2017|archive-date=August 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809110313/http://www.sslmda.com/html/pressreleases/pr20151026.php|url-status=live}}</ref>

It was proposed that the rocket launch might be [[secondary payload|shared with a separate mission]] named ''Athena'', that would perform a single flyby of asteroid [[2 Pallas]], the third-largest asteroid in the [[Solar System]].<ref name="FRB-20190310">{{cite news|last=Dorminey|first=Bruce|title=Proposed NASA SmallSat Mission Could Be First To Visit Pallas, Our Third Largest Asteroid|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucedorminey/2019/03/10/proposed-nasa-smallsat-mission-could-be-first-to-visit-pallas-our-third-largest-asteroid|work=Forbes|date=March 10, 2019|access-date=March 10, 2019|archive-date=August 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809110316/https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucedorminey/2019/03/10/proposed-nasa-smallsat-mission-could-be-first-to-visit-pallas-our-third-largest-asteroid/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In May 2020, it was announced that the Falcon Heavy carrying ''Psyche'' would include two [[Small satellite|smallsat]] secondary payloads to study the Martian atmosphere and binary asteroids, named ''[[EscaPADE]]'' (''Escape and Plasma Acceleration and Dynamics Explorers'') and ''[[Janus (spacecraft)|Janus]]'' respectively,<ref name="sdc20200522" /> but in September 2020, the ''EscaPADE'' Mars atmosphere probe was removed from the plan.<ref>[https://twitter.com/jeff_foust/status/1305526413257211904 The EscaPADE smallsat mission to study the Martian atmosphere has passed PDR, but won't launch with Psyche as originally planned; will be remanifested on a future flight] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200914152112/https://twitter.com/jeff_foust/status/1305526413257211904 |date=September 14, 2020 }} Jeff Foust, SpaceNews, September 14, 2020</ref>

''Janus'' was later removed from the ''Psyche'' mission as well on November 18, 2022, after an assessment determined that it would not be on the required trajectory to meet its science requirements as a result of ''Psyche's'' new launch period.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Janus Mission Removed from 2023 Psyche Launch Manifest – Janus |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/janus/2022/11/18/janus-mission-removed-from-2023-psyche-launch-manifest/ |access-date=2022-11-20 |website=blogs.nasa.gov |date=November 18, 2022 |language=en-US |archive-date=November 25, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221125152144/https://blogs.nasa.gov/janus/2022/11/18/janus-mission-removed-from-2023-psyche-launch-manifest/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Science goals and objectives ===
