The spacecraft uses [[Ion thruster|ion propulsion]]. It has four SPT-140 engines, which are [[Hall-effect thruster]]s using [[solar electric propulsion]], where electricity generated from solar panels is transmitted to an electric, rather than chemically powered, rocket engine.<ref name='SEP 2017'/><ref name='SFI 2017'>{{cite news|url=http://www.spaceflightinsider.com/space-centers/glenn-research-center/nasa-glenn-tests-solar-electric-propulsion-thruster-journey-metal-world/|title=NASA Glenn tests solar electric propulsion thruster for journey to metal world|publisher=Spaceflight Insider|first=Michael|last=Cole|date=October 9, 2017|access-date=January 6, 2018|archive-date=January 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107181930/http://www.spaceflightinsider.com/space-centers/glenn-research-center/nasa-glenn-tests-solar-electric-propulsion-thruster-journey-metal-world/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/centers/glenn/about/fs21grc.html|title=NASA – Ion Propulsion|last=DeFelice|first=David|publisher=NASA|date=August 18, 2015|access-date=January 20, 2018|archive-date=December 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231081317/https://www.nasa.gov/centers/glenn/about/fs21grc.html|url-status=live}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> The thruster is nominally rated at 4.5&nbsp;kW operating power,<ref name='U of MI'>{{cite web|url=http://pepl.engin.umich.edu/project/t-140/|title=T-140|publisher=University of Michigan Plasmadynamics & Electric Propulsion Laboratory|access-date=January 6, 2018|archive-date=June 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617171051/http://pepl.engin.umich.edu/project/t-140/|url-status=live}}</ref> but it will also operate for long durations at about 900 watts.<ref name='SFI 2017'/> ''Psyche'' is the first interplanetary mission to use Hall-effect thrusters, although not the first to use electric thrusters in general.<ref name="Oh2017"/>

The SPT-140 (SPT stands for ''[[Hall-effect thruster|Stationary Plasma Thruster]]'') is a production line commercial propulsion system<ref name='Gerrit 2015'/> that was invented in the USSR by [[OKB Fakel]] and developed by NASA's [[Glenn Research Center]], [[SSL (company)|Space Systems/Loral]], and [[Pratt & Whitney]] since the late 1980s.<ref name="NK">{{cite web|url=http://novosti-kosmonavtiki.ru/content/numbers/198/35.shtml|title=Native Electric Propulsion Engines Today|publisher=Novosti Kosmonavtiki|date=1999|issue=7|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606033558/http://www.novosti-kosmonavtiki.ru/content/numbers/198/35.shtml|archive-date=June 6, 2011|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference|title=Qualification of the SPT-140 for use on Western Spacecraft|conference=50th AIAA/ASME/SAE/ASEE Joint Propulsion Conference, July 28–30, 2014, Cleveland, Ohio|first1=Jorge J.|last1=Delgado|first2=Ronald L.|last2=Corey|first3=Vjacheslav M. |last3=Murashko|first4=Alexander I.|last4=Koryakin|first5=Sergei Y.|last5=Pridanikov|date=2014|id=AIAA 2014–3606|doi=10.2514/6.2014-3606}}</ref> The SPT-140 thruster was first tested in the US at the [[Plasmadynamics and Electric Propulsion Laboratory]] in 1997,<ref>{{Cite web |title=SPT-140 {{!}} UM PEPL |url=https://pepl.engin.umich.edu/project/spt-140/ |access-date=2023-10-20 |language=en-US}}</ref> and later as a 3.5&nbsp;kW unit in 2002 as part of the Air Force Integrated High Payoff Rocket Propulsion Technology program.<ref name='U of MI'/><ref name='Gerrit 2015'>{{cite conference |url=http://2015.spacesymposium.org/sites/default/files/downloads/P.Lord_31st_Space_Symposium_Tech_Track_paper.pdf|title=Evolved Commercial Solar Electric Propulsion: A Foundation for Major Space Exploration Missions|conference=31st Space Symposium, Technical Track, April 13–14, 2015, Colorado Springs, Colorado|first1=Peter W.|last1=Lord|first2=Gerrit|last2=van Ommering|date=2015|access-date=January 6, 2018|archive-date=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107064430/http://2015.spacesymposium.org/sites/default/files/downloads/P.Lord_31st_Space_Symposium_Tech_Track_paper.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Using solar electric thrusters will allow the spacecraft to arrive at 16 Psyche (located 3.3 [[astronomical unit]]s from Earth) much faster, while consuming less than 10% of the propellant it would need using conventional chemical propulsion.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/solar-electric-propulsion-makes-nasas-psyche-spacecraft-go |title=Solar Electric Propulsion Makes NASA's Psyche Spacecraft Go |date=20 September 2021 |publisher=JPL |access-date=October 14, 2023 |archive-date=October 14, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231014045038/https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/solar-electric-propulsion-makes-nasas-psyche-spacecraft-go |url-status=live }}</ref>
